        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We observe in band 7. The spatially resolved velocity width of our target is estimated to be about 60 km/s while the global line profile can easily reach and potentially exceed 400 km/s (for a spiral galaxy like the Milky Way). Therefore the optimal setup is to have a bandwidth of 2000 MHz (1513.12 km/s) with a resolution of 31.2 MHz (25.22 km/s) so our typical line profile emission is spread between about two and a half independent channels.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We requested an array configuration C36-5 with a spatial resolution of 0.14". Since the expected diameter of the source is 0.8", we will have about 5 resolution elements along the major axis of the galaxy disc. This will guarantees the opportunity of deriving a reliable rotation curve with our 3D approach, as pointed out in the scientific justification. The diameter of the source (&lt;1") is moreover well below the maximum recoverable scale of the requested configuration (2.2").</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We estimated the flux in the [CII] 158 um line (CII 2P3/2 2P1/2) for VVDS-J022533.60-041058.0 (gal1) by using the equivalent width of the [CII] 1334.5 angstrom absorption line detected in the VVDS survey. We obtained a value for the integrated flux of 4.20 +/- 2.16 Jy km/s, where the errors are here taken at the 95% confidence level (2 sigma). We assume that the diameter of the source in [CII] 158 um emission is 0.8", as indicated by the CFHT photometry. Assuming an inclination of the galaxy of 60 degrees, at the spatial resolution of 0.14" the source will cover roughly 15 spatial beams (6 to 30 beams spanning from edge-on to face-on view). This leads to an average integrated flux per synthesized beam of 0.28 +/- 0.14 Jy km/s.

The typical velocity dispersion of the [CII] 158 um emission line is not known. The line is associated with a rather cold phase of the ISM and we can make a comparison with local HI observations. In low-resolution (5-6 beams along the major axis) HI observations of nearby galaxies, the measured line width is dominated by the instrumental broadening (beam smearing) but it is usually lower than 40-50 km/s. At high redshifts, the ISM is likely more turbulent and we might expect an effect of turbulence (intrinsic broadening) added to the instrumental broadening. The effect of the spectral resolution (FWHM=25 km/s) is obviously very small in this context.  All considered, we assume that the typical line width (FWHM) of [CII] is 60 km/s, a value also compatible with the dispersions observed in recombination lines at high-z. We finally obtain an average peak intensity of the line of 4.7 +/- 2.4  mJy (errors at 2 sigma). 

The integration time is calculated from the central fiducial value of the peak intensity, i.e. 4.7 mJy, by requiring that in each spatial resolution element the (average) line is detected at a signal-to-noise ratio S/N=6. Hence, a sensitivity of 0.78 mJy and a total integration time of 1.84 hr (55.4 min on source). This condition implies that, even if the real CII flux is at -2 sigma from the central value (i.e. 2.3 mJy), we would be able to detect the source at a S/N~3, a value that will still allow us to derive a reliable kinematics. With such a sensitivity, we have a probability of 97% that the source is detected at S/N&gt;3 in each resolution element and a 50% probability that the S/N is equal or larger than 6.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
