    <prp:abstract>Understanding the history of mass assembly in the Universe requires a detailed investigation of the dynamics of galaxies at the epoch of galaxy formation. Most studies, until now, have concentrated on quasars and extreme starbursts, with very little information on normal star-forming galaxies, which are the progenitors of the present-day Milky Way. We propose to observe two such galaxies at z=4.1 and z=4.5 using the fine-structure [CII]-158um line. Recently, we developed a new 3D tool to robustly derive the rotation curve and velocity dispersion from datacubes at low spatial resolution. With ALMA we can resolve our targets into at least 5 spatial resolution elements, providing ideal conditions for our method to work. These data will allow us to: i) derive the dark matter content and distribution of Milky-Way galaxies at z &gt; 4, ii) put strong constrains on the gas turbulence and the V/sigma ratio, iii) look for evidence of gas accretion from the IGM.</prp:abstract>
